          "body": "The sixteen months at Ziklag are narrated with spare, unsettling efficiency. David's pattern is consistent: raid, kill all survivors, return to Achish with false intelligence about who he attacked (27:10-11). The moral architecture is double-layered. On one ledger: David is executing something functionally equivalent to the herem (sacred destruction) that Saul failed to carry out against Amalek in chapter 15 — he is eliminating the Geshurites, Girzites, and Amalekites, the ancestral enemies of the covenant people who had resisted Israel from the Exodus onward (Ex. 17:8-16; Num. 14:43-45; 1 Sam. 15:1-9). On another ledger: David's motivation is entirely self-protective. He kills all survivors not out of obedience to divine command but to prevent intelligence from reaching Achish (27:11). The covenantal result and the self-serving method coexist without resolution — a picture of how God's redemptive purposes can move forward even through the morally compromised acts of His own people, without those acts thereby being endorsed. This is not a template for deception; it is an honest portrait of how the elect can be simultaneously used by God and operating below their calling."
