          "body": "The complete absence of God's name from 1 Samuel 27 is not an accident of narrative economy. The Deuteronomistic historian uses divine silence as a theological instrument elsewhere (1 Sam. 28:6 — God does not answer Saul at all). Here the silence is less judgment than description: David has chosen a path that does not consult God, and the narrator honors that choice by narrating it on its own terms. But the canonical reader has access to the Psalter, which may provide David's interior life during this period. Psalm 56 — superscribed 'when the Philistines seized him in Gath' — reads like the spiritual emergency beneath the narrative composure of chapter 21, but it applies equally to the settled exile of chapter 27: 'When I am afraid, I will put my trust in You' (Ps. 56:3). The Psalms and the narrative together show a David more complex than either alone — a man who in the Psalms reaches toward the God he has not consulted in the narrative. This canonical interplay does not excuse the unbelief of 27:1; it explains how a man 'after God's own heart' (13:14) can simultaneously produce lament psalms about trusting God and prose narratives about not doing so. The tension is not contradiction; it is the honest biography of every serious believer who has prayed one thing and lived another."
